english:
  title: Preface to the Collection of the Zhongshun Hall
  author: Lee Saeuk
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Way of Poetry bears great significance. Through it, the transformative influence of the ruler and the hearts of the people are revealed. When the teachings of the age declined, poetry transformed into the Elegies of Qu Yuan. Since the Han dynasty, five- and seven-character verse forms arose, and poetry's transformations reached their zenith. Though ancient and regulated forms stand side by side, with varying degrees of skill, each poet nonetheless cultivates his nature and achieves his intent. Observing the emotional resonance and diction of these works, one can see the rise and fall of the world's fortune as clearly as lines upon one's palm.

    Ro, the old scholar of Kumnam, who served as Minister of Justice, was favored by the late king. He composed linked verses and poems, advancing to the third rank. The gentlemen of the realm admired and praised his work, and he created ninety poems in all—brilliant as gems in the Palace of Jade, dazzling to behold. He volunteered for a mission to Japan. Encountering objects and scenes, his feelings stirred spontaneously into verse—two hundred fifty poems in all. The Chan master of Japan gifted him ten more poems. The historians obtained the originals and kept copies. The officials requested to see them. The nobles and officials in the capital all wished to behold them, competing for copies these thirty years without ceasing.

    The old scholar said: "My eccentricity is eccentricity in the world's eyes. Yet I have risen to the rank of Minister of the Six Ministries. Is this truly eccentricity? I am devoted to poetry, and though my verses may seem thin and austere to those of rich indulgence, they are merely eccentric. How can they impede my affairs? My name is recorded among the collections of learned men—its transmission is assured, and my good fortune is great. Yet scattered as these works are, without unity, I plan to gather them into a single record. Yet I fear they may be difficult to transmit and preserve, so I shall have them carved into wood blocks, that all may obtain copies to read and know that Kumnam has its eccentric scholar."

    Then he came to request my preface. I said: "The Son of Heaven gathered poetry from the feudal states—such was the ancient way. In time, when this collection reaches the officials above, the old scholar's name shall spread yet further. Through him, Japanese poetry shall be transmitted to the Middle Kingdom. This is not merely the old scholar's fortune, but Japan's fortune as well. Moreover, our former king upheld the scholars and his virtue overflowed within and without—this collection of the old scholar shall be a contribution to that legacy. How can I not write this preface in full to place at the beginning of the work? The Zhongshun Hall is where the old scholar dwells in ease. The poems have been organized into several volumes, they say."
  footnotes:
    - The 'Way of Poetry' (詩道) refers to the Confucian understanding of poetry as a vehicle for moral transformation and political reflection.
    - 'The ''transformative influence of the ruler'' (王化) is a key Confucian concept: the notion that the ruler''s virtue influences and transforms the hearts of the people.'
    - The reference to the 'Palace of Jade' (群玉府) evokes the celestial treasure house, comparing the collection to precious gems.
    - The practice of 'gathering poetry from the feudal states' was an ancient Chinese imperial ritual believed to reveal the moral state of the realm through its poetry.
